2.2     Installation

    It is an OEM (original equipment manufacturer) unit which means it
    comes with nothing but the bare CDROM and rather useless manual. No
    mounting screws, no driver software, nothing.

    There are 5 groups of connectors on the CDROM (which is totally sealed
    so there is no exposed PC board or anything like that):

    Power:

      Pretty easy ... just connect it to a spare power cable in your
      machine (assuming one is available).

    Audio Out:

      I don't have a sound cable but use a SHIELDED cable to mimimize
      noise between the CDROM and sound card.

    F.GND (Frame Ground):

      Connect it to the grounded frame that runs on the inside of your
      case. Nothing needs to be done if the CDROM is mounted into a 5.5
      inch bay that is metal as the bay will already be grounded.

    IDE Connector:

      This is a "standard" IDE connector. Use the unused connector on the
      IDE ribbon cable (assuming you have one) to connect the CDROM to the
      controller.  IDE limits you to two drives so you'll have one hard
      disk and one CDROM. No room for expansion unless you are running
      enhanced IDE.

      Note that you may be able to install the cable either way in the
      connector but it definately only works if you plug it in the
      correct way.

      See the section on Controller Info below for more information.
      Actually, read it as it will tell you if you are about to give
      yourself a really big headache.

    MASTER/SLAVE/CSEL Jumpers:

      The CDROM comes from the factory with the master jumpered. This
      jumper must be removed and the slave jumpered if you want to add the
      CDROM to a system that already has a single hard disk drive (there
      can only be one master on the IDE bus).

      I have been told that CSEL is Cable Select. This has to be jumpered
      if the IDE cable is an older style that has a twist in it (like the
      floppy cables have).

---------------------------------------
2.3     Controller Info

    This CDROM is equipped with an IDE connector and uses the ATAPI
    interface (purists please excuse me as I attempt to outline how it
    works for those of us in the real world).

    Sony says they have tested this CDROM with quite a number of
    different regular IDE controller boards with no problems. An
    enhanced IDE controller (EIDE) is NOT required in order to use this
    CDROM. Of course you can use an EIDE controller and it does give
    you some benefits (see the section on Windows below).

    Generic IDE Controllers

      This CDROM will work with generic IDE controllers. Use the unused
      connector on the IDE ribbon cable (assuming you have one) to
      connect the CDROM to the controller.  IDE limits you to two
      drives so you'll have one hard disk and one CDROM. There will
      be no room for add another hard disk. Note that Sony shipped my
      CDROM configured as a master and you must move the jumper to
      slave before things will work.

      Note: One person has told me that he was unable to get his CDROM
      to work with his generic IDE controller. He had a 386 based
      system so the age of his controller MAY have had something to do
      with it.

    Secondary IDE Controllers

      This seems to be a bit of a hit and miss. Some people have
      indicated they can get the CDROM to work when connected to a
      secondary IDE controller and others have not been able to.

      I suspect this has to do with the abilities of your BIOS
      to handle secondary controllers as well as your primary and
      secondary controllers to be configured as such and get along
      with each other.

    Caching Controllers

      Sony indicates that their driver will NOT support caching
      disk controllers and, from what I've read on the net, don't even
      try. Sone caching controllers will support CDROMs but the only
      way you are going to know for sure is to post on the net or
      contact the manufacturer.

      As quoted from a guy on the net ... I remember reading 2-3 days
      ago, <clip> Promise is selling a new BIOS for the 4030VL-2 for
      $12. This BIOS seems to give EIDE compatibility to the controller
      and the ability to add an IDE CDROM.  <clip> with that upgrade,
      he was running a Sony 55E from the 4030VL-2 with no problems.
      Just in case, the tech support line of Promise is 408-452-1180

    Enhanced (EIDE) Controllers

      Quoted from a guy on the net ... You don't need a separate card
      to get 32-bit disk access if you are using an EIDE card such as
      the Promise 2300+.  On that card there is a primary VL-IDE 32-bit
      controller capable of handling 2 IDE drives at Mode 3 data
      transfer rates. There is also a secondary controller which uses
      the 16-bit ISA bus and can handle another 2 IDE devices, albeit
      at a slower data transfer rate. I have 2 HD hooked up to the
      primary controller of my 2300+ and I am able to use 32-bit file
      and disk access using WFWG 3.11 even though the slower slave
      drive is a non-EIDE ATA drive while the master is a newer
      Fast-ATA (EIDE) drive. Both are Seagates. On the secondary
      controller of the 2300+ I have a Sony CDU-55E hooked up. All
      three run fine with no conflicts.


    WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING

    This CDROM is labelled as an OEM CDROM. Sony is most likely
    positioning this CDROM for the OEM market. Ie. Compaq buys 10000 of
    these suckers and installs them all their ZZZZZ model of computers.
    Of course, they can get the tech support/changes to ensure that the
    CDROM works with whatever brand/make/model of controller Compaq is
    using. Us single users are taking a chance.

    There are a huge number of different IDE controllers out there. Most
    people don't know the make/model of their controllers and, in many
    instances, can't even find out as a lot of generic controllers used
    in no-name brand computers (such as mine) have no identification on
    them at all. As a result, I couldn't possibly (even if I wanted to )
    maintain a compatibility map of what works and doesn't.

    If you have a generic IDE controller then it will probably work. If
    you have something "fancy" or "non standard" then it probably won't.
    Unfortunately, it is a hit and miss thing. Example, it has been
    reported that this CDROM will not work with the onboard IDE
    controller in a GateWay system.

