2.4     Sony Adapter

      If the CDROM will not work with your IDE card, Sony has available
      an interface card that will work .The Sony part number for their
      card is ATAPICD.KIT, the local Sony outlet quoted $25 as the price,
      two days from the warehouse.

      Besides the driver disk, you get a data ribbon cable, an audio
      cable, and what appears to be a special purpose IDE card. It is
      identified as a Future Domain IDE-16003 and supports only one
      drive. It also accepts the audio cable and passes the audio
      through to two RCA plugs on the rear mounting bracket.

      The card was configured to use IRQ 15 (addr: 170) but could be
      switched via jumpers to IRQ 10 (addr: 160). The little page that
      came with it is rather cryptic as those things usually are. It
      later talks about IRQ 14 as the option, so I am not sure if there's
      a typo or what.

      The card was plugged in with the defaults.  Everything worked fine.
      (Except for stupid error messages from the CORELCDX.COM driver, see
      below for more information). I already had a plain old 1991
      vintage, generic Taiwan IDE card installed that supports two
      floppies and a Maxtor IDE drive. Everything works fine, including
      32-bit access from Windows for my perm swap file.

