3.0     Software
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------
3.1     Sony DOS Drivers

    Smooth move, Sony. They do NOT supply the drivers required to get the
    CDROM working with DOS. (I guess that is what OEM means).

    The file required is atapi.exe ... a self extracting zip which
    includes the drivers, Corel CDROM extensions, utility programs and
    instructions. It is available from:

    - the Sony BBS (file section 3) at 408-955-5107.
    - uploaded from the BBS to ftp.wimsey.com in the path
      /pub/msdos/drivers/sony/atapi.exe (along with this FAQ).

    The latest version of the driver I downloaded on Jan 21, 1995
    from the Sony BBS and placed on wimsey is 2.19c.

    Corel's CDROM extensions come in the driver package but I am using
    Microsoft's MSCDEX CDROM extensions. See the section below on the
    Corel CDROM extensions.

    A hex dump of the driver indicates that it probably won't work if you
    are using DOS 3.1 or earlier. It does work with DOS 5.0 and DOS 6.2.
    Invoke the device driver in config.sys and MSCDEX.EXE (Microsofts
    CDROM extensions for DOS) in autoexec.bat.

        config.sys:
            device = c:\sony\atapi_cd.sys /d:mscd000 /Q

        autoexec.bat:
            c:\dos\mscdex /D:mscd000 /L:M /M:10 /V


    If you install MSCDEX before SMARTDRV then the CDROM will be cached.
    Use the /U option on the SMARTDRV line to disable CDROM caching.

    ATAPI parameters:

      /D   is used to identify the device driver name.
      /Q   This re-enables the interrupt mask for IDE.  This bit is used
           when IDE hard disk is using IDE interrupt on the same bus with
           CD-ROM drive. If long delay is shown when the accessing IDE
           HD after accessing the CDROM drive, adding this switch may
           solve the delay. I just turned it on and left it there.

    MSCDEX paramters: (DOS 6.2)

      /D   specifies the names of the CDROM device drivers to be used
           (separated by commas)
      /L   specifies the DOS drive letter of of the first CDROM.
           Subsequent CDROMs are "lettered" from the first drive.
      /M   specifies the number of sector buffers. This is what came
           with the ATAPI documentation so I just used that
      /V   specifies MSCDEX to print memory stats on startup.


    HINT - HINT - HINT - HINT - HINT - HINT - HINT - HINT - HINT - HINT

    A number of people have reported that performance and recognition
    problems with this CDROM (and clipping of sound from the CDROM to
    sound cards) have virtually disappeared by getting the newest drivers
    and running MSCDEX before SMARTDRV. The latest driver is 2.17a.


    WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING

    Sony indicates that this is an "unsupported" driver, provided as-is
    with no tech support, etc. and has only been made available to assist
    people in using the CDROM until "proper" drivers have been developed.
    They said it is the responsiblity of the IDE controller card
    manufacturer to provide drivers to enable CDROMs to work with their
    card... if you are using a caching disk controller then you had
    better contact your manufacturer to ensure their drivers support IDE
    CDROMs. The Sony driver will probably NOT work with caching disk
    controller. See the hardware section for more information


    WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING - WARNING

    I doublespaced my hard disk after installing everthing and then ran
    MEMMAKER which put the driver into high memory. My system repeatedly
    hung when trying to access the CDROM until I moved the driver back
    into lower memory. It may work for you but it doesn't for me.


---------------------------------------
3.2     Corel DOS Drivers

    The Sony adapter kit comes with two drivers - ATAPI and CORELCDX. I
    had trouble using CORELCDX and was getting strange error messages.
    Sony tech support recommended just trashing it and using MSCDEX with
    DOS 6.0 or better.  The error messages the driver was producing are a
    result of it not being able to use extended memory. Sony said they
    could be turned off by using a switch as follows:

        CORELCDX /d:sony000 /noxms:0

    Apparently, CORELCDX was an old driver that has been obsoleted by the
    new DOS 6.0 version of MSCDEX.  They weren't sure why it was still
    being distributed on the setup/driver disk.


---------------------------------------
3.3     Windows 3.x

    Read the the warning in the DOS driver section above. If you have
    connected the CDROM to an IDE card then the driver will force you to
    disable 32 bit DISK access under Windows 3.x. (Main group, control
    panels, 386 enhanced, virtual memory button). This could seriously
    affect system performance depending on your system configuration. See
    the section on Testing and Performance below.

    However, 32 bit disk access is available under Windows 3.x if you
    are using a EIDE disk controller card, have your hard disks on the
    primary port and the CDROM on the secondary port.

---------------------------------------
3.4     Windows NT

    NT (both server and workstation) are installed by booting off 3
    supplied floppies. Installation then proceeds from the CD-ROM.

    Part of the boot/install is a detection phase that attempts to
    identify all busses (PCI, EISA, etc), controllers on those busses
    (SCSI, IDE, serial, etc) and finally, any peripherals on those
    controllers (disks, cd-rom; tape is not automatic). During the
    boot/install, the ATAPI driver is automatically installed. I did
    *nothing* special during either the install, nor afterwards to use
    the drive (except reassign drive letters for both disk and cd-rom;
    this was for my own reasons. Use "Disk Administrator" to reassign
    drive letters).

    The 55E is as easy to use with NT as any other drive!

---------------------------------------
3.5     OS/2 (Warp and 2.x)

    A number of people have indicated that OS/2 Warp recognizes the CDROM
    during Warp installation and nothing is required to make the CDROM
    available.

    However, a few people have had problems using this CDROM with OS/2
    Warp. The following solution has been sent to me:

    I have succesfully installed OS/2 Warp from CD with my Sony CDU-55E.
    The problem is that this CDROM seems to be not fully atapi
    compatible. After the first part of the warp installation the system
    restarts and boots warp from hard disk. The installation program is
    called automatically and wants to finish the second part of the
    installation. Now the trouble starts. Warp was unable to find the
    CDROM, stops installation or it just hangs and does nothing at all.

    To solve these problems I downloaded 'atapi.zip' via ftp from
    'software.watson.ibm.com' (/pub/os2fixes/atapi.zip. The description
    for this stuff is in "atapi.package". The file 'atapi.zip' includes
    new files and detailed instructions. I made a copy of the 'disk 1
    for cd installation'. There I added one line to 'config.sys' which
    contains only:

    SET COPYFROMFLOPPY=1

    Then I overwrote three files on the copied disk with new versions
    from the package:

    os2cdrom.dmd
    ibm1s506.add
    ibmidecd.flt

    Then I write protected this disk and started the installation
    procedure from the beginning. Installation went on without any
    trouble and nicely detected the sony cdu55e during 'system
    configuration'.

    An excerpt from the readme file includes:

        -------------------------------------------------------------

        IBM OS/2 2.x / 3.x IDE CD driver for IDE CDROM drives
        November 7,1994

        This package conatins the drivers for IDE CDROM drives

        You MUST use these NEW files to replace the existing copies
        supplied by whatever version of OS/2 you are using.

        -------------------------------------------------------------

