4.0     Testing and Performance
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

    My home system is a 486-SX25, no-name VLB IDE controller, Cirrus VLB
    video board, 8MB memory, Caviar 250MB hard disk, USR 14.4K modem.

    I ran WinBench 3.1 before installing the CDROM and my DiskMark was
    27983. I disabled 32 bit disk access in order to enable the CDROM and
    the DiskMark increased to 36390. Strange but that is the way it goes.

    If you have a caching disk controller and disable 32 bit disk access
    your performance will probably go way down. It does on my machine at
    work.

    Results using CDINDEX (CDROM Benchmark Program. ftp it from site
    oak.oakload.edu  /msdos/cdrom/cdindex.zip or from the mirror site
    wuarchive.wustl.edu  /systems/ibmpc/msdos?.../cdindex.zip. Must have
    a CDROM disk with > 400MB)

        avg access: 260ms
        throughput  306kps
        cpu usage: 60%

    The CDROM performs as I expected, although the CPU utilization seems
    a bit high. This is probably due to the driver/cpu mix.


    Another guy has a 486DX40 with no-name IDE controller:

        avg access: 230ms
        throughput: 300kps
        cpu usage:  30-40%

    Another guy has a 486DX?? with no-name IDE controller:

        avg access: 220ms
        throughput: 310kps
        cpu usage:  25%

